06493nam a22009375i 9781487519605DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875196057 a10.3138/97814875196052doi  a(DE-B1597)539749  a(OCoLC)1119624058  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04aThe Allure of Sports in Western Culture /ced. by John Zilcosky, Marlo A. Burks. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPART I. Introduction -- tIntroduction: The Allure of Sports -- tPART II. Theoretical Perspectives -- t1. Sports/Allure -- t2. “Allure” Constrained by “Ethics”? How Athletic Events Have Engaged Their Spectators -- tPART III. The Ancient World -- t3. The Fading Allure of Greek Athletics -- t4. Wrestling, or the Art of Disentangling Bodies -- t5. The Allure and Ethics of Ancient Aesthetics: Hellenism in the Modern Olympic Movement -- tPART IV. Modern Europe -- t6. Attractive or Repugnant? Foot Races in Eighteenth-Century Germany and Britain -- t7. A Well-Trained Community: Gymnastics for the German Nation -- t8. Importing a German Kampfsport: The Reception and Practice of Japanese Martial Arts in Interwar Germany -- t9. The Ethics and Allure of the Foul in Football -- tPART V. Coda -- t10. Swimming -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhether it is our love of chance and vicarious thrill, our need to release anxiety and aggression, or our appreciation of the arc traced by a ball at a crucial moment – sports draw us in. The Allure of Sports in Western Culture contributes to contemporary debates about the attraction of sports in the West by providing a historical grounding, as well as theoretical perspectives and contextualization. Bringing together the work of literary theorists, historians, and athletes, the volume’s dual emphasis allows us to better understand the historical and ideological reasons for the changing nature of sports’ allure from Ancient Greece and Rome to the modern Olympics. The findings show that allure is shaped by larger forces such as poverty, wealth, and status; changing moral standards; and political and cultural indoctrination. On the other hand, personal and psychological factors play an equally important, if less tangible role: our love for scandal, the seduction of deception and violence, and the physiological intoxication of watching and participating in sports keep us hooked. At the heart of the volume lies the tension between our love for sport and our knowledge of its only barely hidden cruelty, exploitation, and manipulation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aOlympic Games.  aallure of sports.  aathleticism.  ahistory and philosophy of sport.  apsychology of sport.  arecreation and leisure.  asociology of sport.  aspectator sports.  asport and society.  atheory of sports.1 aBurks, Marlo A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarred, Grant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGumbrecht, Hans Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmstaedt, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKittler, Wolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMallinckrodt, Rebekka Von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanzer, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRemijsen, Sofie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu